---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Quickstart"
  description="A practical starting point for shaping CodeArmy as a product and integrating it with Trae Solo."
>
  <section class="container page-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Quickstart</p>
    <h1>Start with a product narrative, not a generic agent shell.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      The first public version of CodeArmy should present a clean story: repo-first orchestration
      for long-running AI coding and research campaigns.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="container page-body split-grid">
    <div>
      <h2>Recommended starting point</h2>
      <ol class="page-list">
        <li>Keep the current runtime code in the Alice repository.</li>
        <li>Use CodeArmy as the public-facing product name.</li>
        <li>Make Trae Solo the primary user-facing entry point.</li>
        <li>Keep CLI and Feishu as secondary entry points.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h2>Initial public package</h2>
      <ul class="page-list">
        <li>Landing page on GitHub Pages</li>
        <li>Focused Quickstart documentation</li>
        <li>How-It-Works narrative</li>
        <li>Research use-case pages</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Technical note</strong>
      This website is intentionally static and GitHub Pages-friendly. It avoids backends, dynamic
      forms, and unnecessary client-side complexity so the product story can evolve quickly.
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Current implementation note</strong>
      The CodeArmy product narrative is being introduced while the runtime still lives in the
      current Alice repository. This keeps the technical transition incremental.
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
